ed": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9980308413505554, "span": {"begin": 1983, "end": 1991}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "estrogen receptor beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9971705079078674, "span": {"begin": 1983, "end": 2005}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9959415197372437, "span": {"begin": 2007, "end": 2014}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999484658241272, "span": {"begin": 2027, "end": 2036}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9956269264221191, "span": {"begin": 2080, "end": 2089}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&alpha", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9551072120666504, "span": {"begin": 2124, "end": 2132}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&beta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9838230013847351, "span": {"begin": 2138, "end": 2146}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995848536491394, "span": {"begin": 2176, "end": 2184}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9288484454154968, "span": {"begin": 2259, "end": 2266}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3107"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "classical", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.6835600733757019, "span": {"begin": 2316, "end": 2325}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9967645406723022, "span": {"begin": 2326, "end": 2334}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.827140212059021, "span": {"begin": 2326, "end": 2343}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&beta", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9034956097602844, "span": {"begin": 2360, "end": 2367}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9990476965904236, "span": {"begin": 2439, "end": 2447}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ERs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9891396164894104, "span": {"begin": 2483, "end": 2486}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2571, "end": 2573}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099", "2069"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ER", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 2612, "end": 2614}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&alpha;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9827597737312317, "span": {"begin": 2695, "end": 2704}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&beta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9857150912284851, "span": {"begin": 2756, "end": 2764}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "granulosa cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7866673469543457, "span": {"begin": 2797, "end": 2812}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&alpha;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.98809814453125, "span": {"begin": 2837, "end": 2846}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ER&beta;", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9929057955741882, "span": {"begin": 2851, "end": 2859}}], "text": "Estrogen receptors are produced in all vertebrates and located in either the cell cytoplasm or nucleus(Bondesson et al., 2015; Eick and Thornton, 2011). Estrogen receptors are localized either in cytoplasm, or on the cell surface.  &nbsp;  Site of action: Stressors (e.g., clomiphene) act on neuronal cell in the hypothalamus, where it inhibits hypothalamic Estrogen Receptors selectively.  Responses at the macromolecular level: Stressors activate the Estrogen Receptor &alpha; in the presence of lower level of estrogen and partially blocks the same for higher level of estrogen and works as antagonist for the Estrogen Receptor &beta;(Trost and Khera, 2014). Stressors appear to act in the brain&#39;s pituitary gland to secrete an increased amount of gonadotropins hormone (GnRH) in hypothalamus leading towards increased GnRH level in blood.   Estrogen Receptor &alpha;: ER&alpha; (Estrogen Receptor &alpha; or NR3A1 or ESR1) - A nuclear receptor and it is activated by the estrogen (sex hormone). Estrogen located at chromosome number 6 ( 6q25.1)  Estrogen Receptor &beta;: &nbsp;ER&beta; (Estrogen Receptor &beta; or NR3A2 or&nbsp; ESR2) &ndash; This is also nuclear receptor and &nbsp;activated by the sex hormone estrogen which is located at chromosome number 14 (14q23.2).&nbsp;I ER&beta; has &nbsp;both N-terminal has DNA binding domain and C-terminal has ligand binding domain. This &nbsp;is localized to the nucleus, cytoplasm, and mitochondria. Selective estrogen receptor modulators (SERM) inhibits the ER&beta;. Drugs used as SERM are clomiphene, tamoxifen, raloxifene etc.  Biological compartments: &nbsp;Estrogen receptors (ER) are present in the plasma membrane. Both ER&alpha; and ER&beta; have diverse functions depending on cells and organs. ERs have also been loacated in cytoplasmic organelles including mitochondria and the endoplasmic reticulum(Levin, 2009). &nbsp;  General role in biology: Estrogen receptors (both estrogen receptor alpha (ER&alpha;) and estrogen receptor beta (ER&beta;) binds the estrogens to promote the the biological functions of estrogens. Depending upon a balance between ER&alpha; and ER&beta; activities in target organs, estrogen signaling is selectively stimulated or inhibited (Welboren et al., 2009). ER&beta; has a high degree of sequence homology with the classical estrogen receptor. Interestingly, ER&beta; is detected in many tissues, including those previously assumed to be estrogen insensitive. In tissues where both ERs are expressed, such as the hypothalamus, uterus, mammary glands, and immune system, ER&alpha; promotes proliferation whereas ER&beta; has pro-apoptotic and pro-differentiating functions(Morani et al., 2008). ER&alpha; is present mainly in ovary (thecal cells) where as ER&beta; is found mainly in &nbsp;ovary (granulosa cells)(Paterni et al., 2014). ER&alpha; and ER&beta; is identical approximately 97% in the DNA-binding domain and approximately 56% in the ligand-binding domain(Dahlman-Wright et al., 2006).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:23:49 +0000 2026"}